ğŸ–¥ï¸ Tour of the AWS Console
ğŸŒ Global Services

(These services are not tied to a specific region â€” they are global by nature.)

IAM (Identity and Access Management) â€“ Manages users, roles, and access permissions.

Route 53 â€“ Global DNS and traffic routing service.

CloudFront â€“ Content Delivery Network (CDN) service for low-latency content delivery.

AWS WAF (Web Application Firewall) â€“ Protects applications from common web threats.

ğŸ¢ Region-Scoped Services

(These services are provisioned inside a selected AWS Region.)

Amazon EC2 (Compute) â€“ Virtual servers running applications (IaaS).

Elastic Beanstalk (Platform Deployment) â€“ Deploy and manage applications without managing infrastructure (PaaS).

AWS Lambda (Serverless Compute) â€“ Run code without provisioning servers (FaaS).

Amazon Rekognition (AI/ML) â€“ Image and video analysis using machine learning (SaaS).

ğŸŒ How to Choose an AWS Region

Compliance & Data Residency â€“ Choose a region based on legal or regulatory requirements; data stays in that region.

Latency & Proximity to Users â€“ Select the region closest to your customers for fastest response times.

Service Availability â€“ Not all AWS services are available in every region; newer services launch in select regions first.

Cost Considerations â€“ Pricing varies by region; selecting a lower-cost region can reduce overall spending.
